haracteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dinan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (now mainly counties Clare and Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Daghnáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Daghnán</i>’, possibly a diminutive of <i>dagh</i> ‘good’.","Irish: variant of   Dineen  .","French: habitational name from Dinan, in Côtes-d'Armor, Brittany. This surname is very rare in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Dynan","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Dinan  ."]},{"name":"Dineen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Irish (Cork and Limerick): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinnín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Duinnín</i>’, a byname from a diminutive of <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired man’ or ‘chieftain’."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Emma de Dinan was born about 1130, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert de Vitré, III, Lord of Tillars before 1